div.p:
Unpublished manuscripts by members of Ruskinʼs circle, which have been collected to annotate the edition, include: 
                        Mary Richardsonʼs diary and sketchbook; John James Ruskinʼs earlier diaries and some unpublished letters of later years regarding Ruskinʼs poems; 
                        John James Ruskinʼs and John Ruskinʼs correspondence with the editor, W. H. Harrison, concerning publication of Ruskinʼs poems in annuals throughout the 1830s and 1840s, 
                        and concerning the publication of Poems by J.R. in 1850; Harrisonʼs marked set of printerʼs proofs for Poems by J.R.; 
                        W. G. Collingwoodʼs marked set of printerʼs proofs of Poems (1891); Collingwoodʼs annotated catalog for his 1900 exhibition of Ruskinʼs drawings and manuscripts; 
                        and George Allenʼs correspondence with John Ruskin, Ruskinʼs editors and executors, and Allen’s family. Later editorsʼ papers include: 
                        Cook and Wedderburnʼs records of editing the Library Edition, such as their scrapbook of newspaper clippings of reviews and other notices, 
                        their annotations of Poems (1891), and bound volumes of transcripts; and the Viljoen Papers. Some materials that it is hoped can be sifted in the future include juvenilia by the 
                        children of Ruskinʼs first tutor, Edward Andrews; and the records of Ruskinʼs years as an Oxford undergraduate.
